fields.physical_description:
Beam or Bressumer (portion), the front carved with a scrolling design of grapes and vine leaves.  Removed in 1927 from the front of 122 Fleet Street, City of London.

About 1600.
fields.bibliography:
From: H. Clifford Smith, Catalogue of English Furniture & Woodwork (London 1930), 689
Beam or Bressumer (portion), the front carved with a scrolling design of grapes and vine leaves.  Removed in 1927 from the front of 122 Fleet Street, City of London.

About 1600.
From catalogue H. 1 ft. 3 in., W. 4 ft., D. 1 ft.
(H. 38.1 cm, W. 121.9 cm, D. 30.5 cm)

Given by Professor A. E. Richardson, F.R.I.B.A.

The beam was originally 10 ft. 8 in. (325.1 cm) long, but the carving being entirely defaced, the beam has since been sawn in half and only part of it is preserved.  It is supposed that the beam formed part of an ancient building on this site which was destroyed in the Great Fire of London and was re-used as a bressumer in the old position.  The property, which was sold in 1927, at one time formed part of the land belonging to St. Bride's Church opposite.
fields.credit: Given by Professor A. E. Richardson, F.R.I.B.A.
